1. e4 Nc6 2. Nf3 f5
{ The Colorado Gambit, a gambit so ugly only your mother could love it. } 3.
exf5 d5 { Black tries to retain the pawn with Bxf5. } 4. Bb5
{ The simplest move as it develops the bishop to an active square. } 4... Bxf5
5. Ne5 { Threatening   6.Bxc6  bxc6  which would wreck Black's structure. }
5... Qd6
{ This is the mainline, trying to break the annoying pieces honing on c6. } 6.
d4 { Taking space. } 6... Nf6 { Developing and the most normal move. } 7. O-O
{ The most natural move. } 7... Nd7 { Black tries to break the pin. } 8. Bxc6
{ White damages the pawn structure. } 8... bxc6 9. Bf4
{ Protects the knight on e5. White also has discovered attacks threatened at some point. Often, you'll find that c4 is a good move to play in these types of positions. }
9... Qb4 10. b3
{ The computer likes this move the most because it wants to play c4 at some point and prevent Qxb2. There are also some ways to try to gain a grip on the dark squares with Nd2-Nb3  (after a3-b4)  . }
