[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 1.d4 openings"]
[Black "Englund Gambit 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5 { The Englund gambit. } 2. dxe5 { Taking is best. } 2... Nc6
{ This is Black's only move to try to recuperate the pawn } 3. Nf3
{ Defending it. } 3... Qe7
{ I know Nc3 is a playable move here, but a fun refutation is the mainline I give. Any move other than Qe7 leaves Black down a pawn for nothing. }
4. Bf4 { Defending e5 and forces Black's response. } 4... Qb4+ 5. Bd2
{ The retreating bishop move looks like it doesn't gain much for White, but we will see why this is a strong idea. }
5... Qe7 6. Nc3
{ Now that Black has wasted 2 tempi  (white has Bd2, Nc3 compared with Bf4 earlier)  , it is okay to let Black take on e5. White is obviously doing great after: }
6... Nxe5 7. e4 Nf6 8. Nxe5 Qxe5 9. f4 Qe6 10. Qf3
{ White's next move will be to castle queenside and will have a powerful initiative. }
*

