1. d4 e5 { The Englund gambit. } 2. dxe5 { Taking is best. } 2... Nc6
{ This is Black's only move to try to recuperate the pawn } 3. Nf3
{ Defending it. } 3... Qe7
{ I know Nc3 is a playable move here, but a fun refutation is the mainline I give. Any move other than Qe7 leaves Black down a pawn for nothing. }
4. Bf4 { Defending e5 and forces Black's response. } 4... Qb4+ 5. Bd2
{ The retreating bishop move looks like it doesn't gain much for White, but we will see why this is a strong idea. }
5... Qxb2
{ The prospects of a retreating move like Qe7 are not promising. It looks silly to play Qe7, so this is the only choice. }
6. Nc3
{ The only move, but a good one. Note that 6. Bc3 doesn't work because of the line:   6.Bc3  Bb4  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1#  which is standard knowledge of the Englund. }
6... Bb4
{ The only move that both develops and pressure one of White's pieces. } 7. Rb1
Qxc3
{ This is Aman Hambleton's favorite move. It's losing of course, but he plays it versus his Twitch stream subs. }
8. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 9. Nd2 Bxe5
{ Aman's idea is that he has two pieces and a pawn for the queen. I think he's nuts to play like this, but he plays it because he wants to entertain his subs. Giving material odds to his opponents helps accomplish that objective. White will continue with simple developing moves from here and proceed to win. }
10. e3 { Allows the light-squared bishop to move. } 10... Nf6 11. Bb5 O-O 12.
O-O d5 13. Nf3 Bd6 14. c4
{ This variation needs no comment and White was winning in Zierk, S vs Hambleton, A. Black is down too much material for the queen. Rest in peace to this twitch stream subscriber opening. }
