{ This is Black's only move to try to recuperate the pawn } 3. Nf3
{ Defending it. } 3... f6 4. e4
{ Black hopes to accelerate his development here. Taking the pawn is probably okay, but I like declining it and thereby developing.   Preparing to move the light-squared bishop to c4, with devastating effect. }
4... fxe5 5. Bc4
{ A concept I found funny is that   5.Bb5  transposes to a Schliemann gambit. Of course, Bb5 is not a good move here and, instead, Bc4 is far more annoying. }
5... Nf6
{ Black is pretending that he can develop normally. Rest assured, there is an obvious way to punish his silly play. }
6. Ng5
{ Alas, Nf7 is a huge threat and black has no great reply other than to play a poor Italian Two-Knights variation with something like   6...d5  7.exd5  Na5  8.Bd3  Qxd5  9.O-O  which is losing. }
