1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ The Budapest Gambit: an opening that I think is interesting for Black, but it is good for White if played right. }
3. dxe5 { White should take, of course. } 3... Ng4
{ Black has also played Ne4, but White is simply better in all lines there. Black wants to recoup this pawn as quickly as possible. I say, give it to him, but improve your position in return. }
4. e3
{ This quiet move comfortably keeps a stable advantage as we will see with White's next move. }
4... Nxe5
{ It looks like Black has no weaknesses and White hasn't done much, but White as a surprisingly strong move with... }
5. Nh3
{ This strange, but powerful knight sortie leaves Black questioning how they should develop with less space. White plans to play Nf4 to maintain a nice space advantage and grip on d5. }
5... Bb4+ { Black's most common move. The alternatives aren't as nice. } 6. Bd2
{ White blocks with the poor bishop and is happy to trade it off. Nd2 is okay as well. }
6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2
{ The knight belongs on c3 and the queen is happy to keep an eye on the d-file. A sample line may continue: }
7... d6 8. Nf4 O-O 9. Nc3 a5
{ This is not Black's only try, but I use it as a means to show how White should generally continue in this opening. }
10. Be2 Na6 11. O-O Nc5 12. b3
{ Leaves White simply better. The extra space, the slightly better pieces, and the good central control all contribute towards to White's advantage. }
