1. g4 { The Grob's opening. One of Chess's most memified openings. } 1... e5
{ I like this simple pawn thrust. 1..d5 is good too. } 2. Bg2
{ White develops his bishop to g2 to make use of the g2 square. Otherwise, what was the point of 1. g4 ? }
2... d5
{ Ne7  (planning Ng6-Nh4 which is really annoying for White)  and h5 are fine moves, but I like the simple pawn thrust. }
3. d4
{ I think this is the relatively best move. It's confrontational and lets White pretend he is active. }
3... exd4 4. Qxd4 Be6 { Protecting d5 before Nc6 is played. } 5. Nf3
{ What else does White play ? } 5... Nc6 6. Qa4 Nf6 { Simply developing. } 7.
Ne5
{ This is the only that remotely looks interesting for White. It's fortunately met with a powerful sacrifice: }
7... Bd6 { Gives away c6 to complete development. } 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7
{ White's queen lacks great squares. } 10. Qc3 Bxg4
{ Grabs the pawn back at no cost. If White greedily grabs d5, they will be met yet another powerful sacrifice in: }
11. Bxd5 O-O { Sacrificing the exchange. } 12. Bxa8 Qxa8
{ Re8 is Black's next move } 13. f3 Re8
{ And Black will have a massive attack. Bxf3 is already threatened. If you feel uncomfortable with this position, you can always play 2..Ne7 or 2..h5. They are equally as good as the line I propose here. }
